e used for calibration). The check mark shows the component to be used as a reference. To set parameters for the standards of any component, click on the corresponding line and then click the }{\b Edit }{button. An  }{\ul Edit Standard Dialog Box}{
\v\dbch\af23 \hich\af0\dbch\af23\loch\f0 ID_EDITSTANDARDDIALOG}{ will pop up which allows to fill in the concentration of the selected component in the standard (up to four standards can be used), and to check the particular component as a reference one. 

\par    The }{\b Calibration}{ button opens the }{\uldb Calibration Graph Window}{\v\dbch\af23 \hich\af0\dbch\af23\loch\f0 ID_CAL\hich\af0\dbch\af23\loch\f0 IBRATIONDIALOG}{
 that displays the graph of the selected component's concentration as a function of the component's peak height. In case of a multiple standard calibration, the graph is drawn as straight lines between the successive calibration points from t
he calibration runs made with available standards (the origin is included as the case of zero concentration), and reflects the linear approximation approach between the nearest calibration points (the ones above and below the particular peak height) used 
in calculations of the concentrations of the components from the analysis data. In case the calibration was done with the only standard, the linear approximation is used (a straight line through the calibration point and the origin).   
