at the bottom of the main window show the current operation being executed by the GC. However, if some important parameters/conditions are beyond the normal limits, the diagnostics alarm signal is sent out, and the following messages inform you on the err
ors:
\par }\pard \ql \li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {\b\cf6 Lamp error}{ \endash  the FID or PID lamp or/and the High Voltage Board are not working properly. 
\par }{\b\cf6 Oven temperature low}{ - the oven temperature was 10 or more degrees below the value set as the }{\b Oven Temperature}{ in the }{\uldb Method Dialog Box}{\v ID_METHODDIALOG}{. The messag
e disappears, and the diagnostics alarm goes OFF, if the temperature is back to no more than 2 degrees below the }{\b Oven Temperature}{ value.
\par }{\b\cf6 A/D board error}{\b  }{\endash  the A/D board is not functioning properly. This results in incorrect reading the temperatures and the
 detector signals. The message disappears, and the diagnostics alarm goes OFF, if the board functioning is restored. Otherwise, the GC should be turned off, and the board should be replaced. 
\par }{\b\cf6 Calibration failed in continuous mode}{\b  }{\endash  the calibration failed t
hree times in a row, and the GC operation has been stopped. Check if the retention time of the calibration gas peak on the chromatogram corresponds to the value set in the }{\uldb Standard Dialog Box}{\v ID_STANDARDSDIALOG}{
. Check if the calibration gas cylinder is not empty.
